ure |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330195939/http://moda.ca/attabotics-hq/ |archivedate=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=canarch>{{Cite journal |title=ATTAbotics Headquarters |url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/attabotics-headquarters/ |work=Canadian Architect |volume=64 |number=12 |page=24 |date=December 2019 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=waf>{{Cite web |title=WAF 2019: Day 1 Winners Announced  |url=https://www.archdaily.com/929658/waf-2019-day-1-winners-announced |work=ArchDaily |date=2019-12-04 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> It is designed like a [[wedge]] to conform with nearby [[Calgary Airport]] height restrictions.<ref name=cao>{{Cite web |last=Cao |first=Lilly |title=MoDA's Attabotics Headquarters is Inspired by Ant Colonies |url=https://www.archdaily.com/926001/modas-attabotics-headquarters-is-inspired-by-ant-colonies |work=ArchDaily |date=2019-10-06 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite news |title=Nordstrom partners with tech companies for faster delivery |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rr4WtXooSpo |publisher=CNBC Television |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.attabotics.com Official website]\n\n[[:Category:2016 establishments in Alberta]]\n[[:Category:Companies based in Calgary]]\n[[:Category:Companies established in 2003]]\n[[:Category:Technology companies of Canada]]\n[[:Category:Canadian companies established in 2016]]\n[[:Category:Technology companies established in 2016]]\n", "name_user": "M.nelson", "label": "safe", "comment": "un-draftify", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attabotics"}
{"title_page": "Sendai River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name              = Sendai River\n| name_native       = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd\n| image             = Sakuradote02 1920.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_caption     = [[Cherry]] blossoms along the banks of the Sendai River, in Chizu ch\u014d, [[Tottori, Tottori|Tottori]], [[Tottori Prefecture]]\n| source1_location  = [[Okinosen]] and [[Mount Nagi]]\n| mouth_location    = [[Japan Sea]]\n| mouth_coordinates = {{coord|41|01|00|N|140|22|00|E|region:JP|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Japan]]\n| length            = {{convert|52|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| source1_elevation = \n| mouth_elevation   = {{convert|0|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg    = {{convert|47.55|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}\n| basin_size        = {{convert|1190|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n}}\nThe {{nihongo|'''Sendai River'''|\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd|Sendai-gawa}} is a river in eastern [[Tottori Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. The Sendai is {{convert|52|km|mi|sp=us}} in length and has a drainage area of {{convert|1190|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}. The source of the river is in the [[Ch\u016bgoku Mountains]]. The Sendai flows north through Tottori Prefecture into the [[Sea of Japan]].<ref name=\"n\" /> Under the [[Rivers Act of 1964]] it is designated a Class 1 River, and is managed by the [[Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism (Japan)|Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism]]. About 200,000 people live along the course of the river.<ref name=\"mlit\">{{cite web | url = http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/nihon_kawa/87069/87069-1.html\n| script-title=ja:\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | year = 2007 | publisher = Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese |trans-title=Sendai River | accessdate = Aug 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"chimei\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei | title = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Sendai River | id = dlc 2009238904 | oclc = 173191044 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"d\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Sendai River | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> The Sendai River provides [[sediment]] to form the [[Tottori Sand Dunes]], the largest [[dune]] system in Japan.<ref name=\"n-sakyu\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u9ce5\u53d6\u7802\u4e18 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Tottori Sand Dunes | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"yogai\">{{cite web | url = http://www.cgr.mlit.go.jp/tottori/river/seibi/pdf/keikaku01.pdf | script-title=ja:\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd\u6c34\u7cfb\u306e\u6982\u8981 | year = 2007 | publisher = Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese |trans-title=Sendai River: Overview | accessdate =  Aug 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Sendai river.JPG|thumb|left|Middle reaches of the Sendai River, Chizu, Tottori Prefecture]]\n\n===Upper reaches===\n\nThe source of the Sendai River is in the vicinity of [[Okinosen]] ({{Convert|1318.8|m|ft}}) and [[Mount Nagi]] ({{Convert|1255|m|ft}}), deep in the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains on the border of Tottori and [[Okayama Prefecture|Okayama]] prefectures. Several tributaries of the Sendai similarly emerge from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains in this area, and form a fan-shaped area before flowing into the main course of the Sendai River. The region of gorges and ravines is commonly known as {{Nihongo|\u5cef\u5c90|H\u014dki}} by residents of the area.<ref name=\"n\" /> The upper reaches of the Sendai and its tributaries is protected as part of [[Hy\u014dnosen-Ushiroyama-Nagisan Quasi-National Park]] ({{convert|488.03|km2|mi2}}), established in 1969.<ref name=\"n\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u6c37\u30ce\u5c71\u5f8c\u5c71\u90a3\u5c90\u5c71\u56fd\u5b9a\u516c\u5712 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-07-10 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Hy\u014dnosen-Ushiroyama-Nagisan Kokutei K\u014den | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"d\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = \u90a3\u5c90\u5c71 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Mount Nagi | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n===Middle reaches===\n\nIn its middle reaches the Sendai River emerges from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains and flows northward through the [[Tottori Plain]]. The microrelief of the Tottori Plain reveals that the Sendai once meandered across the plain, rather than following a straight course.<ref name=\"d\" /> Two major canals have been constructed from the Sendai on the Tottori Plain: the {{Nihongo|Yamashirogawa Canal|\u5c71\u767d\u5ddd\u7528\u6c34|Yamashiro-gawa Y\u014dsui}} from its right (eastern) bank, and the {{Nihongo|\u014cide Canal|\u5927\u4e95\u624b\u7528\u6c34|\u014cide-gawa Y\u014dsui}}, also known as the \u014cide River, from its left (western) bank. Original construction on the \u014cide Canal was carried out in 1600 by the feudal lord {{Nihongo|[[Kamei Korenori]]|\u4e80\u4e95\u6b66\u8535|}} (1557 &ndash; 1612) in order to open arable land in the region.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei | title = \u5927\u4e95\u624b\u7528\u6c34 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = \u014cide Canal | id = dlc 2009238904 | oclc = 173191044 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Kokushi Daijiten | title = \u4e80\u4e95\u8332\u77e9 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Kamei Korenori | oclc = 683276033 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> The history of the construction of the Yamashirogawa Canal is unclear; the remaining earthworks suggest a history similar to that of the \u014cide. The [[Ikeda clan]], rulers of [[Tottori Castle]] throughout the [[Edo period]], recorded significant work on the [[Fukuro River]] directly north of the canal, but left no written record of work on the Yamashirogawa. The Sendai and its canals currently provide irrigation for {{Convert|7600|ha|acre}} of rice [[paddy field|paddies]] in the Tottori Plain.<ref name=\"n\"/>\n\n===Lower reaches===\n\nThe mouth of the Sendai River is in the Karo district of the city of Tottori, where it empties into the Japan Sea.<ref name=\"n\"/> Sediment from the Sendai River at the Sea of Japan forms the [[Tottori Sand Dunes]].<ref name=\"d\" /> The lowest reaches and the mouth of the Sendai River are protected as part of [[Sanin Kaigan National Park]] ({{convert|87.83|km2|mi2}}), and the Tottori Sand Dunes are designated a [[Monuments of Japan|Natural Monument of Japan]].<ref name=\"mlit\" /> [[Lake Koyama]] ({{convert|6.9|km2|mi2}}), a brackish [[lagoon]] to the west of the mouth of the Sendai River, was once an inlet of the Sea of Japan. Sediments from the Sendai blocked the mouth of the inlet over time, separating Lake Koyama from the Sea of Japan.<ref name=\"mlit\">{{cite web | url = http://www.asia-planet.net/japan/tottori.htm\n| title = Tottori | year = 2002 | publisher = Orasia Co., Ltd. | accessdate = Aug 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = \u6e56\u5c71\u6c60 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Lake Koyama | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u6e56\u5c71\u6c60 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Lake Koyama | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n===Jurisdictions===\n[[File:Sendai river Mochigase.jpg|thumb|right|Sendai River at Mochigase, Tottori]]\n*Tottori Prefecture\n**[[Tottori, Tottori|City of Tottori]]\n**[[Chizu, Tottori|Chizu]]\n\n===Tributaries===\n\nThe tributaries of the Sendai River emerge from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains and flow through low-lying valleys and tableland in the eastern reaches of Tottori Prefecture. Several tributaries are dammed to produce [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric]] power. There are approximately 71 tributaries of the Sendai, and the major tributaries include:\n\n* {{Nihongo|[[Saji River]]|\u4f50\u6cbb\u5ddd|Saji-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Hatt\u014d River]]|\u516b\u6771\u5ddd|Hatt\u014d-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Sunami River]]|\u7802\u898b\u5ddd|Sunami-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Kisaichi River]]|\u79c1\u90fd\u5ddd|Kisaichi-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Fukuro River]]|\u888b\u5ddd|Fukuro-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Nosaka River]]|\u91ce\u5742\u5ddd|Nosaka-gawa}}<ref name=\"n\" /><ref name=\"mlit\" /><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei | title = \u91ce\u5742\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-14 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Nosaka River | id = dlc 2009238904 | oclc = 173191044 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Tottori Sand Dunes==\n\nThe Sendai River is essential to the formation of the [[Tottori Sand Dunes]], which with an area of {{convert|30|km2|mi2}} are the largest dune system in Japan.<ref name=\"d\"/> The dunes were created by and are replenished by [[granite|granitic]] deposits, specifically [[quartz]], [[feldspar]], [[Lithic fragment (geology)|lithic fragments]], and [[amphibole]]. The sediments are carried from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains down the river into the [[Sea of Japan]]. Fine sand from the sediments of the Sendai is carried back to the shore by [[Current (ocean)|currents]] and [[tide]]s of the Sea of Japan, and then blown by wind to form the dunes.<ref name=\"mlit\" /><ref name=\"n-sakyu\" /> The Hamasaka area of the Tottori Sand Dunes, directly east of the mouth of the Sendai River, is {{Convert|4|km|mi}} and {{Convert|1|km|mi}} wide. The Hamasaka sand dune has little vegetation and is considered the best-preserved dune of the system.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tamura | first1 = Toru | last2 = Bateman | first2 = Mark D. |date=September 2011 | title = Building of shore-oblique transverse dune ridges revealed by ground-penetrating radar and optical dating over the last 500 years on Tottori coast, Japan Sea | journal = Geomorphology | volume = 132 | issue = 3\u20134 | pages = 153\u2013166 | location = Amsterdam, The Netherlands | publisher = Elsevier | doi = 10.1016/j.geomorph.2011.05.005 }}</ref> The Tottori Sand Dunes have shrunk by approximately {{Convert|130|ft|m}} between 1947 and 2003, in part due to the construction of [[sea wall]]s at the Port of Tottori.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =Onishi | first1 = Norimitsu | date= 23 August 2006 | title = In the Shrinking Dunes, Stalking a Creepy Green Enemy | journal = New York Times | pages = 4 | location = New York, N.Y. | publisher =New York Times Company | accessdate = Aug 21, 2012 | url = http://www.lexisnexis.com/}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental conditions==\n\nIllegal dumping of household garbage by residents on the Sendai River, notably on the Fukuro River tributary, is an ongoing environmental problems. Signs pointing out the illegality of dumping have been posted since 2009, and although there has been a reduction of dumping, the problem remains.<ref name=\"nihonkai\">{{cite news | script-title=ja:\u5f8c\u7d76\u305f\u306c\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd\u3078\u306e\u4e0d\u6cd5\u6295\u68c4\u3000\u76e3\u8996\u3001\u5553\u767a\u3092\u5f37\u5316 | url = http://www.nnn.co.jp/news/120819/20120819010.html | newspaper = \u65e5\u672c\u6d77\u65b0\u805e [Nihonkai Shinbun] | publisher = Shin Nihonkai Shinbunsha | date = Aug 19, 2012 | accessdate = Aug 20, 2012 | language = Japanese |trans-title=Continuous Unlawful Dumping of Garbage in the Sendai River: Strengthening Surveillance, Public Awareness}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\n\nThe areas near the mouth of the Sendai are noted for plant species which thrive in sandy areas, notably ''[[Calystegia soldanella]]'', the beach morning glory. Stands of [[Japanese Black Pine|black pine]]s are found in the same area. ''[[Miscanthus sacchariflorus]]'', or Amur silver-grass, is found in the lower reaches of the Sendai where the river has a weaker current. ''[[Celtis jessoensis]]'', the Japanese hackberry, and ''[[Aphananthe aspera]]'', the Muku tree, are found along the lowest {{Convert|10|km|mi}} of the river.<ref name=\"mlit\" />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Tottori port.JPG|thumb|left|Sendai River at the [[Port of Tottori]]]]\nThe Sendai River crossed historical [[Inaba Province]], which made up the eastern half of present-day Tottori Prefecture. The river was used for transportation from early times, and as an inland water transportation link after the development of rice paddies on the middle reaches of the river.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Kokushi Daijiten | title = \u56e0\u5e61\u56fd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Inaba Province | oclc = 683276033 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> Rice was transported from the Tottori Plain south to the port at the mouth of the river.<ref name=\"n\"/> The Sendai River flowed near the ''j\u014dkamachi'' ([[castle town]]) that emerged with the construction of [[Tottori Castle]] during the [[Sengoku period]]. The ''j\u014dkamachi'' sat on low, damp ground, and suffered repeated damage due to flooding on the Sendai.<ref name=\"n\"/> In a 250-year period from the mid-18th century to the early 20th century, the Sendai flooded 100 times, roughly every three years. The urbanization of the city of Sendai caused even more frequent flooding.<ref name=\"mlit\" />\n\nFlood control works were carried out on the Sendai early in the 20th century. A major crook of the river above the mouth of the Sendai was straightened, and the river significantly widened, in 1930. The Fukuro River, a major tributary of the Sendai which meets the Sendai in Tottori City, had a new course excavated in 1934.<ref name=\"n\"/><ref name=\"mlit\" /> The port at Tottori was heavily damaged by the [[1943 Tottori earthquake|Tottori earthquake of 1943]] and a large fire in 1952.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Japan encyclopedia | last1 = Louis-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric | title = Tottori | year = 2002 | publisher = Belknap Press of Harvard University Press | location = Cambridge, Mass. | page = 990 |isbn = 9780674007703 | lccn = 2001052570 | oclc = 48943301}}</ref> A plan to expand the [[Port of Tottori]] and straighten the lowest reaches of the river was made in this period. Construction of wharfs at the mouth of the river was completed in 1983.<ref name=\"n\"/><ref name=\"mlit\" /> Typhoon Number 10 in 1998 caused a landslide behind a quarry along the Sendai. About 50,000 cubic meters of rock were dumped into the river.<ref name=\"yogai\" /><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kodama | first1 = Y. | last2 = Kobayashi | first2 = T. | title = Sediment Pulse Migration And Stopping Along The Sendai River, Japan | journal = American Geophysical Union, Fall Meeting |year=2003 | location = Tokyo | publisher =Nihon Chishitsu Gakkai | language = Japanese }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\nThe tradition of floating dolls on the river, or ''nagashibina'', began along the shallow rapids of the middle part of the Sendai River. The tradition continues today and is designated an Intangible Cultural Asset of Tottori Prefecture.<ref name=\"mlit\" /> ''Insh\u016b-gami'', a type of ''[[washi]]'', or Japanese paper, was produced on the Sendai River from the early [[Edo period]] (1603 &ndash; 1868), and its production was regulated by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]]. The paper is still produced in [[Chizu, Tottori|Chizu]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Kokushi Daijiten | title = \u56e0\u5dde\u7d19 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Insh\u016b-gami | oclc = 683276033 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\nSeveral roads and railroad lines follow the path of the Sendai River. The [[Chizu Line]] of the [[Chizu Express]] follows the river from [[Yamasato Station]] to [[Chizu Station]]. The [[West Japan Railway Company|JR West]] Inbi Line follows the Sendai from Chizu Station to [[Tottori Station]]. The [[Tottori Expressway]] follows the course of the river from its source to Tottori City. [[Japan National Route 53]] and [[Japan National Route 373]] follow the course of the Sendai in Chizu.<ref name=\"yogai\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/nihon_kawa/87069/87069-1.html Sendai River, Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism]{{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.cgr.mlit.go.jp/tottori/livecam_river/index.html \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd: \u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30ab\u30e1\u30e9]{{in lang|ja}} Live camera views of the Sendai River at five locations along the river. Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism.\n\n{{Rivers of Japan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Tottori Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name              = Sendai River\n| name_native       = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd\n| image             = Sakuradote02 1920.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_caption     = [[Cherry]] blossoms along the banks of the Sendai River, in Chizu ch\u014d, [[Tottori, Tottori|Tottori]], [[Tottori Prefecture]]\n| source1_location  = [[Okinosen]] and [[Mount Nagi]]\n| mouth_location    = [[Japan Sea]]\n| mouth_coordinates = {{coord|41|01|00|N|140|22|00|E|region:JP|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Japan]]\n| length            = {{convert|52|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| source1_elevation = \n| mouth_elevation   = {{convert|0|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg    = {{convert|47.55|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}\n| basin_size        = {{convert|1190|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n}}\nThe {{nihongo|'''Sendai River'''|\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd|Sendai-gawa}} is a river in eastern [[Tottori Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. The Sendai is {{convert|52|km|mi|sp=us}} in length and has a drainage area of {{convert|1190|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}. The source of the river is in the [[Ch\u016bgoku Mountains]]. The Sendai flows north through Tottori Prefecture into the [[Sea of Japan]].<ref name=\"n\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-13 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Sendai River | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> Under the [[Rivers Act of 1964]] it is designated a Class 1 River, and is managed by the [[Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism (Japan)|Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism]]. About 200,000 people live along the course of the river.<ref name=\"mlit\">{{cite web | url = http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/nihon_kawa/87069/87069-1.html\n| script-title=ja:\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | year = 2007 | publisher = Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese |trans-title=Sendai River | accessdate = Aug 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"chimei\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei | title = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Sendai River | id = dlc 2009238904 | oclc = 173191044 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"d\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Sendai River | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> The Sendai River provides [[sediment]] to form the [[Tottori Sand Dunes]], the largest [[dune]] system in Japan.<ref name=\"n-sakyu\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u9ce5\u53d6\u7802\u4e18 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Tottori Sand Dunes | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"yogai\">{{cite web | url = http://www.cgr.mlit.go.jp/tottori/river/seibi/pdf/keikaku01.pdf | script-title=ja:\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd\u6c34\u7cfb\u306e\u6982\u8981 | year = 2007 | publisher = Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese |trans-title=Sendai River: Overview | accessdate =  Aug 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Sendai river.JPG|thumb|left|Middle reaches of the Sendai River, Chizu, Tottori Prefecture]]\n\n===Upper reaches===\n\nThe source of the Sendai River is in the vicinity of [[Okinosen]] ({{Convert|1318.8|m|ft}}) and [[Mount Nagi]] ({{Convert|1255|m|ft}}), deep in the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains on the border of Tottori and [[Okayama Prefecture|Okayama]] prefectures. Several tributaries of the Sendai similarly emerge from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains in this area, and form a fan-shaped area before flowing into the main course of the Sendai River. The region of gorges and ravines is commonly known as {{Nihongo|\u5cef\u5c90|H\u014dki}} by residents of the area.<ref name=\"n\" /> The upper reaches of the Sendai and its tributaries is protected as part of [[Hy\u014dnosen-Ushiroyama-Nagisan Quasi-National Park]] ({{convert|488.03|km2|mi2}}), established in 1969.<ref name=\"n\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u6c37\u30ce\u5c71\u5f8c\u5c71\u90a3\u5c90\u5c71\u56fd\u5b9a\u516c\u5712 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-07-10 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Hy\u014dnosen-Ushiroyama-Nagisan Kokutei K\u014den | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"d\">{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = \u90a3\u5c90\u5c71 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Mount Nagi | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n===Middle reaches===\n\nIn its middle reaches the Sendai River emerges from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains and flows northward through the [[Tottori Plain]]. The microrelief of the Tottori Plain reveals that the Sendai once meandered across the plain, rather than following a straight course.<ref name=\"d\" /> Two major canals have been constructed from the Sendai on the Tottori Plain: the {{Nihongo|Yamashirogawa Canal|\u5c71\u767d\u5ddd\u7528\u6c34|Yamashiro-gawa Y\u014dsui}} from its right (eastern) bank, and the {{Nihongo|\u014cide Canal|\u5927\u4e95\u624b\u7528\u6c34|\u014cide-gawa Y\u014dsui}}, also known as the \u014cide River, from its left (western) bank. Original construction on the \u014cide Canal was carried out in 1600 by the feudal lord {{Nihongo|[[Kamei Korenori]]|\u4e80\u4e95\u6b66\u8535|}} (1557 &ndash; 1612) in order to open arable land in the region.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei | title = \u5927\u4e95\u624b\u7528\u6c34 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = \u014cide Canal | id = dlc 2009238904 | oclc = 173191044 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Kokushi Daijiten | title = \u4e80\u4e95\u8332\u77e9 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Kamei Korenori | oclc = 683276033 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> The history of the construction of the Yamashirogawa Canal is unclear; the remaining earthworks suggest a history similar to that of the \u014cide. The [[Ikeda clan]], rulers of [[Tottori Castle]] throughout the [[Edo period]], recorded significant work on the [[Fukuro River]] directly north of the canal, but left no written record of work on the Yamashirogawa. The Sendai and its canals currently provide irrigation for {{Convert|7600|ha|acre}} of rice [[paddy field|paddies]] in the Tottori Plain.<ref name=\"n\"/>\n\n===Lower reaches===\n\nThe mouth of the Sendai River is in the Karo district of the city of Tottori, where it empties into the Japan Sea.<ref name=\"n\"/> Sediment from the Sendai River at the Sea of Japan forms the [[Tottori Sand Dunes]].<ref name=\"d\" /> The lowest reaches and the mouth of the Sendai River are protected as part of [[Sanin Kaigan National Park]] ({{convert|87.83|km2|mi2}}), and the Tottori Sand Dunes are designated a [[Monuments of Japan|Natural Monument of Japan]].<ref name=\"mlit\" /> [[Lake Koyama]] ({{convert|6.9|km2|mi2}}), a brackish [[lagoon]] to the west of the mouth of the Sendai River, was once an inlet of the Sea of Japan. Sediments from the Sendai blocked the mouth of the inlet over time, separating Lake Koyama from the Sea of Japan.<ref name=\"mlit\">{{cite web | url = http://www.asia-planet.net/japan/tottori.htm\n| title = Tottori | year = 2002 | publisher = Orasia Co., Ltd. | accessdate = Aug 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Dijitaru Daijisen | title = \u6e56\u5c71\u6c60 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Lake Koyama | oclc = 56431036 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Daihyakka Zensho (Nipponika) | title = \u6e56\u5c71\u6c60 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-12 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Lake Koyama | oclc = 153301537 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n===Jurisdictions===\n[[File:Sendai river Mochigase.jpg|thumb|right|Sendai River at Mochigase, Tottori]]\n*Tottori Prefecture\n**[[Tottori, Tottori|City of Tottori]]\n**[[Chizu, Tottori|Chizu]]\n\n===Tributaries===\n\nThe tributaries of the Sendai River emerge from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains and flow through low-lying valleys and tableland in the eastern reaches of Tottori Prefecture. Several tributaries are dammed to produce [[hydroelectricity|hydroelectric]] power. There are approximately 71 tributaries of the Sendai, and the major tributaries include:\n\n* {{Nihongo|[[Saji River]]|\u4f50\u6cbb\u5ddd|Saji-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Hatt\u014d River]]|\u516b\u6771\u5ddd|Hatt\u014d-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Sunami River]]|\u7802\u898b\u5ddd|Sunami-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Kisaichi River]]|\u79c1\u90fd\u5ddd|Kisaichi-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Fukuro River]]|\u888b\u5ddd|Fukuro-gawa}}\n* {{Nihongo|[[Nosaka River]]|\u91ce\u5742\u5ddd|Nosaka-gawa}}<ref name=\"n\" /><ref name=\"mlit\" /><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Nihon Rekishi Chimei Taikei | title = \u91ce\u5742\u5ddd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-14 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Nosaka River | id = dlc 2009238904 | oclc = 173191044 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Tottori Sand Dunes==\n\nThe Sendai River is essential to the formation of the [[Tottori Sand Dunes]], which with an area of {{convert|30|km2|mi2}} are the largest dune system in Japan.<ref name=\"d\"/> The dunes were created by and are replenished by [[granite|granitic]] deposits, specifically [[quartz]], [[feldspar]], [[Lithic fragment (geology)|lithic fragments]], and [[amphibole]]. The sediments are carried from the Ch\u016bgoku Mountains down the river into the [[Sea of Japan]]. Fine sand from the sediments of the Sendai is carried back to the shore by [[Current (ocean)|currents]] and [[tide]]s of the Sea of Japan, and then blown by wind to form the dunes.<ref name=\"mlit\" /><ref name=\"n-sakyu\" /> The Hamasaka area of the Tottori Sand Dunes, directly east of the mouth of the Sendai River, is {{Convert|4|km|mi}} and {{Convert|1|km|mi}} wide. The Hamasaka sand dune has little vegetation and is considered the best-preserved dune of the system.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Tamura | first1 = Toru | last2 = Bateman | first2 = Mark D. |date=September 2011 | title = Building of shore-oblique transverse dune ridges revealed by ground-penetrating radar and optical dating over the last 500 years on Tottori coast, Japan Sea | journal = Geomorphology | volume = 132 | issue = 3\u20134 | pages = 153\u2013166 | location = Amsterdam, The Netherlands | publisher = Elsevier | doi = 10.1016/j.geomorph.2011.05.005 }}</ref> The Tottori Sand Dunes have shrunk by approximately {{Convert|130|ft|m}} between 1947 and 2003, in part due to the construction of [[sea wall]]s at the Port of Tottori.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =Onishi | first1 = Norimitsu | date= 23 August 2006 | title = In the Shrinking Dunes, Stalking a Creepy Green Enemy | journal = New York Times | pages = 4 | location = New York, N.Y. | publisher =New York Times Company | accessdate = Aug 21, 2012 | url = http://www.lexisnexis.com/}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental conditions==\n\nIllegal dumping of household garbage by residents on the Sendai River, notably on the Fukuro River tributary, is an ongoing environmental problems. Signs pointing out the illegality of dumping have been posted since 2009, and although there has been a reduction of dumping, the problem remains.<ref name=\"nihonkai\">{{cite news | script-title=ja:\u5f8c\u7d76\u305f\u306c\u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd\u3078\u306e\u4e0d\u6cd5\u6295\u68c4\u3000\u76e3\u8996\u3001\u5553\u767a\u3092\u5f37\u5316 | url = http://www.nnn.co.jp/news/120819/20120819010.html | newspaper = \u65e5\u672c\u6d77\u65b0\u805e [Nihonkai Shinbun] | publisher = Shin Nihonkai Shinbunsha | date = Aug 19, 2012 | accessdate = Aug 20, 2012 | language = Japanese |trans-title=Continuous Unlawful Dumping of Garbage in the Sendai River: Strengthening Surveillance, Public Awareness}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\n\nThe areas near the mouth of the Sendai are noted for plant species which thrive in sandy areas, notably ''[[Calystegia soldanella]]'', the beach morning glory. Stands of [[Japanese Black Pine|black pine]]s are found in the same area. ''[[Miscanthus sacchariflorus]]'', or Amur silver-grass, is found in the lower reaches of the Sendai where the river has a weaker current. ''[[Celtis jessoensis]]'', the Japanese hackberry, and ''[[Aphananthe aspera]]'', the Muku tree, are found along the lowest {{Convert|10|km|mi}} of the river.<ref name=\"mlit\" />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Tottori port.JPG|thumb|left|Sendai River at the [[Port of Tottori]]]]\nThe Sendai River crossed historical [[Inaba Province]], which made up the eastern half of present-day Tottori Prefecture. The river was used for transportation from early times, and as an inland water transportation link after the development of rice paddies on the middle reaches of the river.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Kokushi Daijiten | title = \u56e0\u5e61\u56fd | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Inaba Province | oclc = 683276033 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref> Rice was transported from the Tottori Plain south to the port at the mouth of the river.<ref name=\"n\"/> The Sendai River flowed near the ''j\u014dkamachi'' ([[castle town]]) that emerged with the construction of [[Tottori Castle]] during the [[Sengoku period]]. The ''j\u014dkamachi'' sat on low, damp ground, and suffered repeated damage due to flooding on the Sendai.<ref name=\"n\"/> In a 250-year period from the mid-18th century to the early 20th century, the Sendai flooded 100 times, roughly every three years. The urbanization of the city of Sendai caused even more frequent flooding.<ref name=\"mlit\" />\n\nFlood control works were carried out on the Sendai early in the 20th century. A major crook of the river above the mouth of the Sendai was straightened, and the river significantly widened, in 1930. The Fukuro River, a major tributary of the Sendai which meets the Sendai in Tottori City, had a new course excavated in 1934.<ref name=\"n\"/><ref name=\"mlit\" /> The port at Tottori was heavily damaged by the [[1943 Tottori earthquake|Tottori earthquake of 1943]] and a large fire in 1952.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Japan encyclopedia | last1 = Louis-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric | title = Tottori | year = 2002 | publisher = Belknap Press of Harvard University Press | location = Cambridge, Mass. | page = 990 |isbn = 9780674007703 | lccn = 2001052570 | oclc = 48943301}}</ref> A plan to expand the [[Port of Tottori]] and straighten the lowest reaches of the river was made in this period. Construction of wharfs at the mouth of the river was completed in 1983.<ref name=\"n\"/><ref name=\"mlit\" /> Typhoon Number 10 in 1998 caused a landslide behind a quarry along the Sendai. About 50,000 cubic meters of rock were dumped into the river.<ref name=\"yogai\" /><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kodama | first1 = Y. | last2 = Kobayashi | first2 = T. | title = Sediment Pulse Migration And Stopping Along The Sendai River, Japan | journal = American Geophysical Union, Fall Meeting |year=2003 | location = Tokyo | publisher =Nihon Chishitsu Gakkai | language = Japanese }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\nThe tradition of floating dolls on the river, or ''nagashibina'', began along the shallow rapids of the middle part of the Sendai River. The tradition continues today and is designated an Intangible Cultural Asset of Tottori Prefecture.<ref name=\"mlit\" /> ''Insh\u016b-gami'', a type of ''[[washi]]'', or Japanese paper, was produced on the Sendai River from the early [[Edo period]] (1603 &ndash; 1868), and its production was regulated by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]]. The paper is still produced in [[Chizu, Tottori|Chizu]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Kokushi Daijiten | title = \u56e0\u5dde\u7d19 | url = http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | accessdate = 2012-08-20 | year = 2012 | publisher = Shogakukan | location = Tokyo | language = Japanese | trans-title = Insh\u016b-gami | oclc = 683276033 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ | archivedate = 2007-08-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\nSeveral roads and railroad lines follow the path of the Sendai River. The [[Chizu Line]] of the [[Chizu Express]] follows the river from [[Yamasato Station]] to [[Chizu Station]]. The [[West Japan Railway Company|JR West]] Inbi Line follows the Sendai from Chizu Station to [[Tottori Station]]. The [[Tottori Expressway]] follows the course of the river from its source to Tottori City. [[Japan National Route 53]] and [[Japan National Route 373]] follow the course of the Sendai in Chizu.<ref name=\"yogai\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mlit.go.jp/river/toukei_chousa/kasen/jiten/nihon_kawa/87069/87069-1.html Sendai River, Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism]{{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.cgr.mlit.go.jp/tottori/livecam_river/index.html \u5343\u4ee3\u5ddd: \u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30ab\u30e1\u30e9]{{in lang|ja}} Live camera views of the Sendai River at five locations along the river. Japanese Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism.\n\n{{Rivers of Japan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Tottori Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sendai_River"}
{"title_page": "Roy Leonard", "text_new": "{{Infobox presenter\n|name       = Roy Leonard\n|alias      = \n|image      = \n|imagesize  = \n|caption    =\n|birth_name  =LeRoy Stewart Leonard\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1931|1|19}}\n|birth_place = [[Redwood Falls, Minnesota]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|2014|9|4|1931|1|19}}\n|death_place = [[Evanston, Illinois]]\n|show       = \n|station    = [[WGN (AM)|WGN]], [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], USA\n|timeslot   = \n|show2      = \n|station2   = \n|timeslot2  =\n|style      = \n|country    = [[United States]]\n|prevshow   = \n|web        = \n}}\n'''LeRoy Stewart Leonard'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://royleonard.com/?page_id=418|title=Roy Leonard biography|publisher=Roy Leonard.com|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> (January 19, 1931 \u2013 September 4, 2014) was an [[United States|American]] [[radio personality]], best known for hosting [[WGN (AM)|WGN]]'s midday [[Radio programming|radio show]] from [[Chicago]] for 31 years and for his appearances on [[WGN-TV]]'s news and Christmas specials.  He also hosted [[Family Classics]] after [[Frazier Thomas]] died.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-04-03/features/9804030139_1_wgn-independent-tv-stations-bob-bell|title=At 50, WGN Finds The TV Picture and Audiences Have Changed|author=Johnson, Allan|date= April 3, 1988|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|accessdate= February 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLeonard died on September 4, 2014 at a hospital in [[Evanston, Illinois]] of complications from an esophageal infection, aged 83.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); No By-line-->|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20140904/news/140909160/|title=Chicago broadcasting legend Roy Leonard dies|date= September 4, 2014|newspaper=Daily Herald|accessdate= September 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Chris|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/news/chi-roy-leonard-obituary-column.html|title=Roy Leonard, beloved WGN Radio personality, is dead at 83|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=September 5, 2014|date=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Feder |title=Roy Leonard prefers to stay put at WGN |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3868612.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025072842/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3868612.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=February 4, 1988 |accessdate=April 7, 2009}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.wgngold.com/people/leonard-roy.htm |title=Roy Leonard |accessdate=April 7, 2009 |publisher=WGN Radio |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831021009/http://www.wgngold.com/people/leonard-roy.htm |archivedate=August 31, 2012 }}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.wgnradio.com/shows/leonard_roy/index.html |title=The Roy Leonard Show |accessdate=April 17, 2009 |publisher=WGN Radio |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981202104110/http://www.wgnradio.com/shows/leonard_roy/index.html |archivedate=December 2, 1998}}\n*{{cite news |first=Donald |last=Liebenson |title=Everybody loves Roy: for 25 years, Leonard has put us in tune with show-biz greats |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=August 9, 1992}}\n*{{cite news |first=Clarence |last=Peterson |title=3 'Awards' for WGN's Roy Leonard |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=March 4, 1971}}\n*{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Deeb |title=Roy Leonard: Unique but unsung |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 30, 1975}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1585912}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leonard, Roy}}\n[[Category:American radio DJs]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bulls broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs broadcasters]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from Redwood Falls, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category